### Description

It would be cool to add the ability to return signals from pipe, and automatically read them. Some pipes can change the result over time (because of a timer, or some data in the dependent service has changed, etc.). It is not very good to make them impure, as this can affect performance. Pipe can now return signals, but their use looks ugly. I would like native support.

### Proposed solution

countdown.pipe.ts
```typescript
import type {PipeTransform, Signal} from '@angular/core';
import {Pipe, computed} from '@angular/core';
import {toSignal} from '@angular/core/rxjs-interop';
import {interval} from 'rxjs';

const tickTimeout = 100;

@Pipe({
    name: `countdown`,
    standalone: true,
})
export class CountdownPipe implements PipeTransform {
    readonly #tick = toSignal(interval(tickTimeout), {
        initialValue: -1,
    });

    public transform(value: number, stepInterval = 1000): Signal<number> {
        const startTick = this.#tick();

        return computed(() =>
            Math.ceil(value - ((this.#tick() - startTick) * tickTimeout) / stepInterval),
        );
    }
}
```

app.component.html
```
{{ 20 | countdown }}
```

Also need add support for the pipes chain, some of which may be signal-pipe, and some may not:
```
{{ value | signalPipe | plainPipe | otherSignalPipe }}
```

### Current workaround

app.component.html
```
{{ (20 | countdown)() }}
```

```
{{ ((value | signalPipe)() | plainPipe | otherSignalPipe)() }}
```

The import manager ensures generation of unique identifiers when inserting imports. This is done by inspecting existing identifiers within the original source file, while also checking if a similar identifier was generated at an earlier time. This is correct behavior.

We can improve the detection so that the same identifier can be generated in different files. This is beneficial for schematic/migration use-cases where we wouldn't want to generate import aliases in multiple files just because we generated an import to e.g. `input` previously.

E.g. it's fine to generate

```ts
// a.ts
import {input} from '@angular/core';

// b.ts
import {input} from '@angular/core';
// instead of: input as input_1.

```

